I have always passed by this restaurant, but only just visited for the first time this weekend with some friends. We were NOT expecting the high level of service we received - every single staff member (not just our specific server) was incredibly friendly and attentive. There was a packed house and we still received our food so quickly (within 3-4 mins of ordering each time) and were constantly checked up on by other staff as well, who were happy to bring us extra plates, cutlery, and glasses as needed. Happy hour food, drinks, and prices were great - unique selection of sushi as well as classic appetizers like fried calamari, Brussel sprouts, pork buns. Beautiful plating and exceptional drinks like the lychee martini, ginger Champagne, and the lounge lemonade. We had the absolute pleasure of having a server named Shayna - she was so friendly, funny, and had great recommendations for the food drinks and best seating locations. At the end of the evening, the manager came out to talk to our table and ask us where we were from and how we decided to visit. Truly an exceptionally special experience which made us realize it's been a long time since we've had service like this at any restaurant in the DMV area. Both the food and the service were equally spectacular and we will be back many more times! If you haven't been before, you must go!

I was in the area with one of my Lenders and we decided to try Sushiko for Happy Hour.  We were there on a Sunay, so it wasn't very busy.  I ordered the lychee martini which was a little on the sweet side, but good.  The martini also has a lychee for garnishment. The lychee is a tropical tree native to the Guangdong and Fujian which are provinces of China.  The main producer of lychee fruit is China.  My Lender ordered lounge lemonade and very good!! Not bad for $5.  We also ordered the spicy salmon avacado, the shrimp tempura and the crunchy spicy avocado.  They were good but I didn't really like the soy paper that these appetizers  are wrapped in.  I gave them a 4 star vs 5 star rating because the chairs in the bar area are town up.  Which I am surprised considering where they are located.

Good value if you go for happy hour.  5 stars for happy hour,  4 star for a dinner. For regular dinner, it is pricey.   Good cocktails.   Try fried brussel sprouts.  They  are delicious.  Hand rolls are decent but I would prefer if they had used nori.

The table next to us that also ordered an omakase echoed the same comments. We also ordered a sashimi omakase that was of a much higher quality than the sashimi in the spring omakase. For the price, I would have much preferred to travel a little further to spots in DC. Although very busy, the service was quick, polite, and very attentive.

Chicken hh option was rubbery. The real highlight was the Brussels sprouts! I wish I had ordered just those, they’re prolly some of the best I’ve ever had. Overall, If your looking for a small gathering spot for cocktails and maybe light fare... not bad as the price point wasn’t bad. But don’t bring a date, you’ll both leave disappointed.

I've wanted to go to Sushiko for a while after hearing good things and being told it was the best place for sushi around Bethesda. The salmon in the maki was chewy & the salmon in the poke bowl was too cold to properly enjoy. The nigri portions were very small but higher quality than the maki. There's a wide variety of fish on the menu that you won't find elsewhere nearby, by be prepared to pay heavily. The staff was all very friendly, as a highlight. We left still hungry and went to buy a pizza. We'll be sticking with Maki Bar for our sushi needs.

Sushiko offers a chance to discover Japanese food beyond sushi and sashimi.  Everything we tried was amazing:  "Sear it yourself" Wagyu beef with yuzu, koshu and ponzu; Seared lobster with enoki mushroom, sauteed spinach, and creamy ponzu;  Yaki tako: Baby octopus 🐙 with yuzu, Asian pear, watermelon radish, and mixed greens;  Kabocha: Japanese winter squash tempura with kaeshi: Flash fried panko oysters with Tonkatsu sauce and mustard; and delicious Fresh water eel roll with spicy tuna, masago, kabayaki sauce, avacado, jalapeno, and pickled ginger. I discovered this place through OpenTable website and making the reservation and modification was really easy. I got a confirmation call within an hour after making the reservation. Had an amazing dinner, went on my husband's birthday and the staff and service was really good, they made the occasion really special. Sushiko offers a complimentary Banana Tempura with ice cream for birthdays, and I mentioned that in my special request to come with a candle. Our waitress offered to take pictures of us to remember the celebration. The hostess offered parking validation through a ticket, when I forgot my parking pass in the car. It was an amazing experience. When I go next time, I will try the soft shell crab, shrimp tempura and seared sea scallops. I will also love to experience various courses at 'Kobo' when Chef Peter Thanks comes back from his July vacation.

As the son of restauranteurs having grown up in the sushi restaurant business for over 20 years I think I should have an understanding of what good sushi is. In my time, I have experienced many different sushi restaurants and worked with many sushi chefs. My experience tells me for the money their are much better sushi to be had at much better prices... unless of course you're easily fooled by the quasi chique atmosphere and wanna be Michelin prices. My order of the 6 piece nigiri chefs sampler was disappointing to say the least. It came with none of the fresh wasabi I was promised and included slices of fish that could of been had at a '$2 a piece' Chinese knock off restaurant. In fact, I've had better or comparable at one of these knock off places. Aside from the sushi the appetizers were OK but nothing striking to speak about. Service was lackluster with the typical Miami trend spot attitude. I would highly recommend finding another place of you are include to look for good sushi in the area.
